25|$|Cranbury was {{originally}} an important hamlet of Hursley, with many distinct farms and cottages, {{but now the}} name belongs only to Cranbury House and Park. The first recorded tenant of Cranbury is a Mr. Shoveller, who surrendered it to Roger <b>Coram</b> before 1580. <b>Coram</b> rented Cranbury at £17 2s per annum from the Lord of the Manor of Merdon, Sir Thomas Clarke.|$|E
25|$|Thomas <b>Coram</b> (c 1688–1751), was {{the founder}} of the Foundling Hospital in London.|$|E
25|$|Although the Judiciary Act of 1789 gave courts {{the power}} to issue writs, the writ of <b>coram</b> nobis {{developed}} slowly. The writ was acknowledged as early as 1834 by the United States Supreme Court when it recognized that its counterpart, the writ of <b>coram</b> vobis, might be available in state courts to challenge an error of fact. Despite this early acknowledgment, the writ of <b>coram</b> nobis, at least federally, was a rather archaic vehicle for relief. In 1881, the United States Supreme Court recognized {{the availability of the}} writ as common-law writ but acknowledged it was not utilized by the courts and even questioned its availability.|$|E
